ed around types of buildings and landscapes, including the Jamaican plantation landscape and fortified houses to the architecture of free blacks. He concludes with a consideration of Jamaican architecture in Britain. By connecting the architecture of the Caribbean first to West Africa and then to Britain, Nelson traces the flow of capital and makes explicit the material, economic, and political networks around the Atlantic.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Apr 2020) 0aArchitecturezJamaicaxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / Regional.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300214352423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300214352.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO